\par \plain\f0\fs22\cf3\b TPJRegWdwState.SubKey
\par \plain\f0\fs12\cf2 
\par \plain\f0\fs18\cf1 \protect <HS 18>\plain\f0\fs18\cf2 TPJRegWdwState\plain\f0\fs18\cf1 \protect </HS 18>\plain\f0\fs18\cf2           \plain\f0\fs18\cf1 \protect <HS 5>\plain\f0\fs18\cf2 See also\plain\f0\fs18\cf1 \protect </HS 5>\plain\f0\fs18\cf2 
\par \plain\f0\fs8\cf2  \plain\f0\fs18\cf1 \protect </NS 17>\plain\f0\fs18\cf2 
\par \plain\f0\fs8\cf2 
\par \plain\f0\fs18\cf2 Determines the registry sub key under which the window's size, position and state information is stored.
\par 
\par \plain\f1\fs18\cf1 \protect <KP 1>\plain\f1\fs18\cf2\b property\plain\f1\fs18\cf2  SubKey: \plain\f1\fs18\cf2\b string\plain\f1\fs18\cf2 ;\plain\f1\fs18\cf1 \protect </KP 1>\plain\f1\fs18\cf2 
\par \plain\f0\fs18\cf2 
\par \plain\f0\fs18\cf2\b Description\plain\f0\fs18\cf2 
\par \plain\f0\fs8\cf2 
\par \plain\f0\fs18\cf2 This property defines the subkey under which the window's size, position and state information is stored in the registry. This subkey is stored under the root key defined by the \plain\f0\fs18\cf1 \protect <HS 4>\plain\f0\fs18\cf2 RootKey\plain\f0\fs18\cf1 \protect </HS 4>\plain\f0\fs18\cf2  property.
\par \plain\f0\fs8\cf2 
\par \plain\f0\fs18\cf2 To ensure that the sub key is relative to the root and not the current key the subkey should begin with a '\\' character.
\par \plain\f0\fs8\cf2 
\par \plain\f0\fs18\cf2 If the property is set to the empty string then it becomes 
\par \plain\f0\fs8\cf2 
\par \pard \li200 \tx200 \plain\f0\fs18\cf1 \protect <KP 2>\plain\f1\fs18\cf2 '\\Software\\<Program EXE filename>\\Window\\<Form Name>'\plain\f1\fs18\cf1 \protect </KP 2>\plain\f0\fs18\cf2 
\par \pard \plain\f0\fs8\cf2 
\par \plain\f0\fs18\cf2 where <Program EXE filename> is the program's executable file name (without the path) and <Form Name> is the name of the form on which the TPJRegWdwState component is placed. For example, if your program is executed from \plain\f0\fs18\cf2\i C:\\MyStuff\\MyProg.exe\plain\f0\fs18\cf2  and the form is named \plain\f0\fs18\cf2\i Form1\plain\f0\fs18\cf2  then setting SubKey := '' causes the property's value to become 
\par \plain\f0\fs8\cf2 
\par \pard \tx200 \plain\f0\fs18\cf1 \protect <KP 3>\plain\f1\fs18\cf2 \tab '\\Software\\MyProg.exe\\Window\\Form1'\plain\f1\fs18\cf1 \protect </KP 3>\plain\f0\fs18\cf2 
\par \pard \plain\f0\fs8\cf2 
\par \plain\f0\fs18\cf2 The default value of the property is the empty string.
\par }

